+Tenhys That's right, this breed is maintained through line breeding, which 
means breeding back to sires or grandsires in order to keep the mutation 
prominent in the gene pool. it's a practice very common in specialized 
breeds and keeps the also common practice of cross breeding from 
eliminating the prominence of the traits. Double muscling was first noticed 
in the 1800s, long before genetic research, and eventually they did figure 
out the exact genetic mutation that causes this condition. One thing to 
note about transgenics is it is not used in animal food production. 
Transgenic crops are used in food production, but it is far too expensive 
time consuming and risky to make an animal in a test tube only for it to 
become steak. Transgenic animals are use for research, such as finding ways 
to produce things in mass quantities so that they are useful to humans, 
like spider silk in goats milk, or getting bacteria to produce insulin for 
humans with diabetes. many people imagine GMOs as a sort of Frankenstein 
project, but that's not quite the case. It involves careful manipulation of 
the DNA modification enzymes that are used naturally, and using them to 
insert genes that species would not normally express. It takes a lot of 
trial and error to ensure the result is not only viable in the first place, 
but can eventually express the desired gene. It's really amazing how we've 
only begun to discover the possibilities of transgenics, and how much is 
already possible. We can save endangered breeds of yak by inserting it's 
DNA into a bovine embryo (if we ever figure out how to restore woolly 
mammoths they'll likely use the same method with African elephants). we can 
make corn that secretes its own insect repellent, eliminating the need for 
artificial pesticides. We can increase the amount of BST a cow produces, 
allowing her to produce more milk for a longer period of time without the 
need to inject the artificial version (which has been banned due to 
negative public opinion). Transgenics are amazing, but we still get the 
majority of the improvement in animal species through selective breeding 
alone. The size of chicken breasts has more than tripled in the last 30 
years just through breeding. the general public opinion is against all this 
stuff, but people forget how important it is that we find ways to produce 
more food with the same or potentially less resources--the human population 
is growing too quickly for us to depend solely on the all-natural route, it 
doesn't produce enough food in enough time to feed 10 billion people by 
2050. That's why I can't stand the "it's not natural therefore it's bad" 
and "GMOs are linked to cancer" arguments, because there is so little 
backing to them, but those arguments are so popular amongst people who have 
never read a scholarly article in their lives.

Learn the relevant definitions. These are:
Cow: a mature female bovine that has given birth to at least one or two 
calves. Colloquially, the term "cow" is also in reference to the Bos 
primigenius species of domestic cattle, regardless of age, gender, breed or 
type. However for most people who work with or raise cattle, this term is 
not used in the same reference as previously noted.
Bull: a mature, intact (testicles present and not removed) male bovine used 
for breeding purposes.
Steer: a male bovine (or bull) that has been castrated before reaching 
sexual maturity and is primarily used for beef.
Stag: a male bovine (or bull) that has been castrated after or upon 
reaching sexual maturity and is primarily used for beef, but can and is 
also often used as a "gomer bull" for detecting cows and heifers in heat.
Heifer: a female bovine (often immature, but beyond the "calf" stage) less 
than 1 to 2 years of age that has never calved. Such females, if they've 
never calved beyond two years of age may also be called heiferettes.
Bred Heifer: a female bovine that is pregnant with her first calf.
First-calf Heifer or First-calver: a female bovine that has given birth to 
her first calf, and is often around 24 to 36 months of age, depending on 
the breed and when she was first bred.
Ox (plural: Oxen): a bovine that is trained for draft work (pulling carts, 
wagons, plows, etc.)This is a term that primarily refers to a male bovine 
that has been castrated after maturity. However, an ox can also be female 
bovine (cow or heifer) or even a bull that has been trained for the same 
purpose. In the Biblical times, an ox was a general term used, just like 
with the term "cows," to a domesticated bovine regardless of age, gender, 
breed, type, or draft purposes.
Calf (plural: Calves): an immature bovine (male and female) that is reliant 
on milk from its dam or from a bottle in order to survive and grow. A calf 
is known as such from birth to around 10 months of age.
Bull calf: an immature intact male bovine (since all males are born with 
testes) that is reliant on milk from his dam or a bottle for growth and 
survival.
Steer calf: an immature male bovine that has been castrated a few days to a 
couple months after birth, and is reliant on milk from his dam or a bottle 
for growth and survival.
Heifer calf: an immature female bovine that is reliant on milk from her dam 
or a bottle for growth and survival.
Freemartin: an infertile or sterile heifer or heifer calf. Such infertility 
is a result of being maternally twinned with a bull calf which placental 
tissues were shared in the womb. During the first trimester, reproductive 
organs start to form and sexual hormones begin to be produced in the fetus. 
When male and female fetal calves are twinned together, the testosterone 
produced by the male inhibits estrogen production in the female. This 
results in abnormal, underdeveloped or hermaphroditic reproductive organs 
in the female fetus. This is not so for the male. Freemartins are sometimes 
referred as "hermaphrodites" if they are born with reproductive organs of 
both genders. As a result, these type of freemartins tend to develop 
secondary male sexual characteristics (muscular crest over neck, wide 
forehead, etc.) upon reaching puberty.
Cattle: general plural term for more than one bovine
Cattlebeast/bovine/animal: a singular term for a bovine whose gender cannot 
be determined, particularly when viewed at a distance. Most people like to 
call a bovine of unknown (or "unknown") gender as a "cow," simply because 
it is a much more well-known and popular term to use than "bovine" or 
"cattle beast." This, however, is often not the case around experienced 
cattlemen and cattle women or "ranchers" (as some like to call them) who 
never use the term "cow" when referring to a bovine that is anything but a 
cow. "Animal," "critter," "creature," or any other term, coarse or not, are 
most often used over the colloquial word "cow."
